<TITLE> Europe shares drop after US data </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares fell on Tuesday after a batch of US data showed retail sales unexpectedly fell in December, aggravating concern about the outlook for growth, while wholesale inflation remained tame. US retail sales -- the ultimate gauge of consumer spending -- fell 0.4 percent, trumping forecasts for a flat reading and exacerbating worries about the potential for recession and the knock-on effect on corporate profits in the world's largest economy. The US government said its producer price index excluding food and energy rose 0.2 percent in December, in line with expectations. Banks were the worst performing sector in Europe, with HSBC down 3.7 percent, Banco Santander off 2.1 percent and Royal Bank of Scotland down 2.9 percent. By 1338 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was down 1.4 percent at 1,411.68 points, having fallen back from a session high of 1,432.85 points. US stock futures were all down about 1 percent. Around Europe, London's FTSE 100 index fell 1.6 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX lost 0.9 percent and Paris' CAC 40 shed 1.2 perce
